      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-03-30_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline>March 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                  <placeName ref=".Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Trim</placeName>
                  <date when="1843-03-30">March 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1843</date></dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p><placeName ref=".Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Trim</placeName> - March 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1843
               Your <hi rend="underline">lark</hi> sang delight<lb/>
               fully at its rising, and in<lb/>
               the whole of its flight &amp;<lb/>
               descent - How much<choice> 
                  <orig>plea<lb/>
                     sure</orig>
                  <reg>pleasure</reg>
               </choice>
               you gave dearest <choice>
                  <orig>mo-<lb/>
                     ther</orig>
                  <reg>mother</reg>
               </choice>
               you can hardly know<lb/>
               unless you could see &amp; hear<lb/>
               behind your back as well<lb/>
               as before your face -<lb/>
               I never was more delighted<lb/>
               than by the surprise of<lb/>
               seeing your dear rosy face<lb/>
               lightening upon me and so<lb/>
               affectionately &amp; unexpectedly<lb/>
               and I only wish I had that<lb/>
               hug over again -<lb/>
               
               We all, - meaning <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1"> Edgeworth, Harriet (née Butler)</persName><lb/>
               &amp; myself<lb/></p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-03-30_page02.jpg"/>
               
            <p>have agreed that under<lb/>
               your staid, prove, every <lb/>
               day demeanour and <lb/>
               matronly <del>habits</del> and<lb/>
               Grandmotherian habits<lb/>
               you have a <hi rend="underline">deal</hi> of romance<lb/>
               deep down that sprouts up<lb/>
               to day unexpectedly every<lb/>
               now and then - Kind <choice>
                <orig>fa<lb/> 
                   ther</orig>
                  <reg>father</reg>
               </choice>
               ther for you - And God bless<lb/>
               you for it - and often may<lb/>
               it sprout for our delight<lb/>
               
               I hope dearest mother<lb/>
               that the pleasure you have<lb/>
               given &amp; received I trust<lb/>
               on this little occasion will<lb/>
               encourage you to indulge<lb/>
               yourself in future when<lb/></p>
            <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-03-30_page03.jpg"/>
               
               <p>ever opportunity &amp; <choice>
                    <orig>tempta-<lb/>
                       tion</orig>
                    <reg>temptation</reg>
               </choice>
                  well join for a <hi rend="underline">Spry</hi>
                  (an American word acknow<lb/>
                  (ledged by American dictionary<lb/>
                  (which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1"> Edgeworth, Harriet (née Butler)</persName> rich in Dic<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>possesses<lb/>
               I am so glad that<lb/>
                  you had the luck at<lb/>
                  the last moment to<lb/>
                  catch the unpacking<lb/>
                  of the picture of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxW1">Fox, Walter</persName><lb/>
                  though between you &amp;<lb/>
                  I it is but a sorry drawing<lb/>
                  and does not suit (in my<lb/>
                  opinion the place where it<lb/>
                  now is viz over the Bishop<lb/>
                  of Meaths admirable head<lb/>
                  and between you &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF2"> Beaufort, Francis Lestock </persName><lb/>
                  I hope <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxM1"> Fox, Mary Anne</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC2"> Edgeworth, Charlotte </persName><lb/>
                  will take it up to their own<lb/></p>
            <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-03-30_page04.jpg"/> 
            
               <p>room - It does not match any<lb/>
                  thing in this room - &amp; I cant<lb/>
                  abide it - But it was very good<lb/>
                  of Aunt <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH2">Beaufort, Henrietta</persName> to get it done<lb/>
                  and to send it to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxM1">Mary Anne</persName> &amp; C<lb/> 
               A new music has just <choice>
                  <orig>ar-<lb/>
                  rived </orig>
                  <reg>arrived</reg>
               </choice>
               &amp; the room is all ears<lb/>
                  And <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Edgeworth, Lucy Jane</persName> is judging - and<lb/>
                  I am no judge but very<lb/> </p>
            <closer>
               affectionately yours<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">ME</persName><lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>I am so glad you have <lb/>
                  Conde - Do you see in<lb/>
                  todays paper the report that<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StanP1">Stanhope, Philip</persName>Lord Mahon is to go <choice>
                     <orig>Embassa<lb/>
                        dor</orig>
                     <reg>Embassador</reg>
                  </choice>
                  to <placeName ref=".Placeography.xml#SP">Spain</placeName> - I hope it is<lb/>
                  done - it would suit &amp;<lb/>
                  gratify him so much<lb/>
                  Thank you for mentioning<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">Sneyd, Mary</persName>Marys delight on her sealed<lb/>
                  packet - Love to all<lb/></p>
            </postscript>
               
         </div>
